{"id":"mindful-eating-6","label":"Mindful Eating: A Path to a Healthy Body","lockAfter":2,"list":[{"id":"notes","type":"passage","label":"Notes","data":{"title":"Food and Nutrients","text":"India is an agricultural country and various crops are grown in different regions depending on the soil and climatic conditions.\nThe choice of food depend on the cultivation in that particular region, culture, and traditions. \nOur cooking practices, also called culinary practices, have changed with the arrival of new technologies.\nThere are different components in our food.\n# Carbohydrates\nThese are one of the primary sources of energy in our diet. Cereals like wheat, rice, and maize, vegetables like potato, and fruits like banana, pineapple, and mango are rich in carbohydrates.\nCommon sugar is also a type of carbohydrate. A marathon runner drinks glucose water during and after a race. Glucose is a carbohydrate that provides instant energy.\n# Fats\nThese are sources of stored energy. Nuts, such as groundnuts, walnuts, coconuts, and almonds, and ghee are sources of fat. Carbohydrates and fats are called energy-giving foods.\nPolar bears accumulate a lot of fat under their skin. This fat serves as an energy source. It supports them during their months-long winter sleep (hibernation), enabling them to survive without eating.\n# Proteins\nProtein rich foods help in growth and repair of our body. These are called body-building foods. Sportspersons need proteins in larger quantities to build their muscles. We get proteins from plants and animals. Some sources are pulses, beans, peas, nuts, milk, paneer, egg, fish, meat.\nThe right amount of protein must be included in the diet of growing children for their proper growth and development. Edible mushrooms are good sources of protein.\n# Scurvy\nIn earlier times, during long voyages, sailors often suffered from bleeding and swollen gums. During a voyage in 1746, Scottish physician James Lind observed that sailors who consumed lemons and oranges recovered from these symptoms. Bleeding and swollen gums are symptoms of a disease called scurvy. It is caused due to deficiency of Vitamin C, which is present in citrus fruits like lemon and orange.\n# Goitre\nIt is a disease whose symptom is, swelling at the front of the neck. In 1960s, it was prevalent in the Himalayan region and the Northern plains of India. Later discovered, it was due to the deficiency of Iodine. The Government of India ensured that Iodine was supplemented in common salt.\n# Nutrients\nFood components that provide energy, support growth, help repair and protect our body from diseases, and maintain various bodily functions are called nutrients. The major nutrients in our food include carbohydrates, proteins, fats, vitamins and minerals.\nVitamins and minerals are also called protective nutrients as they protect us from diseases and keep us healthy. \nSome nutrients like vitamin C and others are lost during cooking due to high heat. It would be wise to have uncooked vegetables and fruits.\n# Roughage\nIn addition to the essential nutrients, our body needs dietary fibres and water. Dietary fibres, also known as roughage, do not provide any nutrients to our body. However, they are an essential component of our food. They help our body get rid of undigested food and ensure smooth passage of stools.\n# Water\nWater is also an essential part of our diet. It helps the body absorb nutrients from food. It removes waste from the body through sweat and urine. We should drink sufficient water regularly to keep ourselves healthy.\nEating food that is locally grown and plant based, to the extent possible, is not only healthy for the body but is also good for our environment and our planet. "}},{"label":"Fill in the blanks","type":"matchByDragDrop","id":"fillup","onlyBigScreen":true,"commonData":{"dashWidth":100,"actWidth":1300,"fontSize":"2rem","dashHeight":"2.7rem","labelsOnSide":true},"data":["Fats are sources of *stored* energy. Polar bears accumulate a lot of *fat* under their skin. This fat serves as an *energy* source. They sleep without food for months during winter, which is called *hibernation*.\nA marathon runner drinks *glucose* water during the race, which gives instant energy.","Carbohydrates and fats are called *energy giving* nutrients.\nVitamins and minerals are called *protective* nutrients.\nProteins are called *body building* nutrients.\nGlucose is a source of *carbohydrates*. Ghee is a source of *fat*. Fish is a source of *protein*. ","*Goitre* is a disease whose symptom is, *swelling* at the front of the neck. In 1960s, it was *prevalent* in the Himalayan region and the Northern plains of India. Later discovered, it was due to the deficiency of *Iodine*. The Government of *India * ensured that Iodine was *supplemented* in common salt."]},{"id":"mcq","label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","data":{"questions":[{"qText":"Which of the following are called energy giving nutrients?","options":"* Carbohydrates\nProteins\nVitamins\n* Fats"},{"qText":"Which of the following are called protective nutrients?","options":"Proteins\n* Vitamins\nFats\n* Minerals"},{"qText":"Glucose is a __________.","options":"carbohydrate, fat, water, fibre"},{"qText":"Scurvy was observed and studied among _____.","options":"sailors\nsoldiers\nfarmers\npoor people"},{"qText":"The symptom for Goitre is ______. ","options":"swollen neck, swollen gums, bleeding gums, headache"},{"qText":"_____ helps the body absorb nutrients from food.","options":"water, glucose, fibre, blood"},{"qText":"Culinary skills mean ______.","options":"cooking skills\nfarming skills\nunderstanding balanced diet\nunderstanding nutrients"}]}},{"label":"True or False","id":"true-false","type":"classifySentence","data":{"title":"Classify the below sentences as true and false","types":[{"name":"True","text":"We have to eat locally grown food as much as possible.\nFats are sources of stored energy.\nProtein rich foods help in growth and repair of our body."},{"name":"False","text":"Vitamin rich foods gives us energy to do work.\nCulinary skills means agricultural skills."}]}},{"id":"fillup-2","label":"Fill Up","type":"fillup","data":{"text":"*Uncooked (Cooked)* vegetables are very healthy.\nIndia is an *agricultural (industrial)* country.\nFruits like banana, and mango are rich in *carbohydrates (fat, protein)*.\n*Protein (Vitamin)* rich foods help in growth and repair of our body.\nFast growing children need lot of *protein (carbohydrates, fat)*.\nDeficiency of Vitamin C leads to *scurvy (goitre)*.\n*Roughage (Water)* help our body get rid of undigested food and ensure smooth passage of stools.\n*Water (Blood)* helps the body absorb nutrients from food."}},{"label":"Pick the right answer.","id":"find-ans","type":"classifySentence","data":{"title":"Classify the below sentences as true and false","variableOptions":true,"text":"_______ vegetables are very healthy. | Uncooked, Cooked\nIndia is an _______ country. | agricultural, industrial\nFruits like banana, and mango are rich in _______. | carbohydrates , fat, protein\n_______ rich foods help in growth and repair of our body. | Protein , Vitamin\nFast growing children need lot of ______. | protein ,carbohydrates, fat\nDeficiency of Vitamin C leads to ______. | scurvy , goitre\n________ help our body get rid of undigested food and ensure smooth passage of stools. | Roughage , Water\n_______ helps the body absorb nutrients from food. | Water , Blood "}},{"id":"notes-2","type":"passage","label":"Notes: Testing food for Nutrients","data":{"title":"Testing food for Nutrients","text":"Some nutrients like starch (a type of carbohydrate), fat, and protein can be detected using fairly simple tests, while others can be detected only in a well-equipped laboratory. \nTake a small quantity of the food items such as a slice of potato, cucumber, bread, some boiled rice, boiled gram, crushed peanuts, oil, butter and crushed coconut.\n# Test for starch\nPlace a small piece of each item on a separate dish. With the help of a dropper, put 2–3 drops of diluted iodine solution on each food item. If the colour changes to blue-black, it indicates the presence of starch.\n# Test for fats\nPlace each food item on a separate piece of paper. Wrap the paper around the food and press it. Be careful not to tear the paper. If a food item contains a little water, allow the paper to dry. Observe the paper through light. If you find any oily patch, the food item contains fat.\n# Test for proteins\nMake a paste or powder of the food item using pestle and mortar. Put about half teaspoon of each food item in a separate clean test tube. Add 2–3 teaspoons of water to each test tube and shake them well. Add two drops of copper sulphate solution to each test tube using a dropper. Now, take another dropper and add 10 drops of caustic soda solution to each tube. Shake well and leave the test tubes undisturbed for a few minutes. If the content turn violet, it indicates the presence of protein.\n# Precaution\nMany chemicals used in the lab are harmful and need to be handled with care. Do not touch any of these chemicals unless asked to do so. If any chemical gets spilled on your body, immediately wash the affected area with water. Do not put any of these chemicals into your mouth, or try to smell them.\n\n "}},{"id":"notes-3","type":"passage","label":"Notes: Balanced Diet","data":{"title":"Balanced Diet","text":"A diet that has all essential nutrients, roughage, and water in the right amount for proper growth and development of the body is known as a balanced diet.\nNutrients requirement is not the same for everyone. It depends on ones age, gender, physical activity, health status, and lifestyle.\n# Junk Foods\nFoods that are high on sugar and fat content, and low on proteins, minerals, vitamins and dietary fibres are called junk foods. They make a person obese, and lead to health problems.\n# Packaged Foods\nPackaged food items must have information about the nutrients on their cover. The information should list the amount of each nutrient. Sometimes, more nutrients are added to the food during processing (fortification) to improve its nutritional quality.\nIodised salt and some baby foods are examples of fortified foods. The Food Safety and Standard Authority of India (FSSAI) is a government agency that regulates food quality in India. \n# Millets\nThey are small-sized grains and have been an integral part of the Indian diet for centuries. They are native crops of India and easily cultivated in different climatic conditions. They are good sources of vitamins, minerals like iron and calcium, and dietary fibres as well. That is the reason they are also called nutri-cereals.\n# Food Miles\nThe entire distance travelled by food items, from the producer to the consumer, is known as its food miles. Reducing food miles helps to cut down the cost and pollution during its transport; it helps support local farmers; and it also keeps our food fresh and healthy. \n# Avoid wasting foods\nMany people waste food, leaving it unconsumed on their plates. One must remember the time and effort put by our farmers and other community members in getting the food from the farm to our plate. We must take only as much food as we can consume. "}},{"id":"mcq-2","label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","data":{"questions":[{"qText":"Presence of which nutrient can be found with the help of iodine solution?","options":"Starch, Fat, Protein, Vitamin"},{"qText":"Which nutrient leaves an oily patch when wrapped in a paper?","options":"Fat, Carbohydrate, Protein, Minerals"},{"qText":"When we test for Protein using copper sulphate and caustic soda solution, for positive result, the color changes to ____.","options":"violet, pink, white, blue"},{"qText":"Which of the following is true for packaged food?","options":"Nutrients information should be printed on the cover.\nAll food items should be iodised.\nAdditional nutrient should be added on natural food.\nOnly solid food items should be packaged."},{"qText":"Which of the following is not true about millet?","options":"Rich in fat and protein\nEasy to cultivate in different climatic condition.\nNative crop of India\nAlso called as nutri-cereals"}]}},{"label":"True or False","id":"true-false-2","type":"classifySentence","data":{"title":"Classify the below sentences as true and false","types":[{"name":"True","text":"Some chemicals are dangerous to touch with hands or smell them. | We have to take lot of precaution while handling chemicals.\nLocally grown food are usually cheap. | No extra cost for transportation and preservation."},{"name":"False","text":"Presence of all nutrients in food item can be verified in school lab. | Only few can be tested in school lab. For many, we need well equipped lab.\nAs millets are healthy, we can have it as food 3 times daily. | We need to take different variety of foods to get a balanced diet. Though millets are healthy, they don't have all nutrients.\nFor balanced diet we have to eat foods grown in different parts of the world. | Not necessary. Locally grown food should be our first priority."}]}},{"id":"match","label":"Match Food and Nutrients","type":"match","data":{"text":"Rice & Bread , Carbohydrates\nGhee & Nuts , Fat\nFish & Paneer , Protein\nCarrot & Orange , Vitamin\nMillets & Dates , Minerals\nWhole grains & Legumes , Fibre","title":"Match Food and Nutrients"}},{"id":"chapati-story","type":"slides2","label":"Story of Chapati","data":{"title":"Story of Chapati: From farm to plate","displayType":"steps","images":"img/science/big/food-from-field-to-table","imgHeight":400,"fontSize":"2rem","steps":[{"text":"Farmers grow the crop in the field.","img":"growing-wheat"},{"text":"Grains are removed from the plant through threshing and winnowing.","img":"threshing"},{"text":"Grains are properly stored and protected from rats and insects.","img":"storing"},{"text":"Grains are grinded and packaged with the help of a machine.","img":"packaging"},{"text":"Packed wheat flour are transported to local shops.","img":"store-display"},{"text":"Our parent buy them, and cook delicious Chapati.","img":"chapati"}]}},{"id":"cooking-old-new","type":"slides2","label":"Old & New way of cooking","data":{"title":"Old & New way of cooking","displayType":"steps","images":"img/science/big/cooking-old-and-new-way","imgHeight":400,"fontSize":"1.5rem","steps":[{"text":"In olden days, cooking was done in a clay stove, using wood as fuel. The cooking was slow, and smoke from burning wood gave health issues.","img":"clay-stove"},{"text":"In modern days, we have gas and electric stoves. The cooking is done fast, and no smoke.","img":"gas-stove"},{"text":"In olden days, there was no electricity or machine, and grinding was manually done using stone grinder.","img":"stone-grinder"},{"text":"In modern days, we have blender and grinder, which helps to quickly grind without manual labour.","img":"mixer"}]}}]}